04218nam a22005535i 9780520353442DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203534427 a10.1525/97805203534422doi  a(DE-B1597)647988  a(OCoLC)1419789001  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aThomas/Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpoilage :bJapanese-American Evacuation and Resettlement During World War II /cThomas/Richard; ed. by Nishimoto Richard, Dorothy Swaine Thomas. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (414 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPREFACE -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tI. EVACUATION: Expulsion of a Minority Group -- tII. DETENTION: Confinement Behind Barbed Wire -- tIII. REGISTRATION: Administrative Determination of "Loyalty" and "Disloyalty" -- tIV. SEGREGATION: Separation of the "Loyal" and "Disloyal" -- tV. REVOLT: Strikes, Threats, and Violence -- tVI. SUPPRESSION: Martial Law -- tVI. ACCOMMODATION: Rise and Fall of the Coordinating Committee -- tVIII. UNDERGROUND: Inception of Resegregationist Pressure -- tIX. INTERLUDE: Period of Apathy -- tX. INFORMERS: Suspicion, Beatings, and Murder -- tXI. INCARCERATION: The Stockade Issue -- tXII. RESEGREGATION: Pressure Tactics of the "Disloyal” -- tXIII. RENUNCIATION: Mass Relinquishment of American Citizenship -- tAPPENDIX -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring World War II, 110,000 citizens and resident aliens of Japanese ancestry were banished from their homes and confined behind barbed wire for two and a half years. No more blatant violation of civil rights has ever been decreed by an American president, yet so strong were the currents of bigotry and war time hysteria that effective political opposition was impossible. However, a group of University of California social scientists, sensing the enormity of the outrage, organized in 1942 to record and analyze the causes, legal and social consequences, and long-term effects of the detention program. The Spoilage, one of a series of books which resulted, analyzes the experiences of that part of the detained group-some 18,000 in total-whose response was to renounce America as a homeland; it shows the steps by which these "disloyal" citizens were inexorably pushed toward the disaster of denationalization. Essentially the result of years of research by participant observers of Japanese ancestry, it is a factual record of enduring value to the student of America's troubled ethnic relations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aRichard, Nishimoto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomas, Dorothy Swaine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052001418340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035344240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520353442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520353442/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles